	   <tr><td colspan=2>What makes a warrior a tank is not only his/her dex and agi, but also their strength and insanely high hp.&nbsp;&nbsp;My 30 barb warrior partner has well over 1000 unbuffed hp, where at lvl 33, my unbuffed barb shaman is a puny 706.  Warrior also has the advantage of dual wield, dishing out more damage than we can with our somewhat slow weapons.<br><br>But why would you want to use your shaman as a "tank with heal buffs" when you've got (or will be getting) some incredible buffs, debuffs, dots and some fairly decent dd's?<br><br>Consider this....A few days ago I dueled a 36 pally friend (buffed 1100 hp) who cons red to me.  Not a duel to the death, but just to very low hp (who wants to do a corpse run as a result of dueling a friend?).  I buffed myself (endure magic, resist cold, resist heat, protect, tutle skin, inner fire, dex, str, agi, sta...okay, basically everything I have) and medded full mana prior to the duel.   I cast malise, root, walking sleep, disempower, envenomed breath, frost strike, affliction, frost strike, re-root,  and frost strike again before we finally called it quits.  Not once did I step in to tank (this pally dual wields like a maniac).<br><br>Final score?<br><br>Human Pally  hp  178/1100<br>Barb Shaman  hp  117/736  (much of my hp loss was a result of cannibalizing for more mana)<br><br>Do the math......Shaman wins!!  (yes, we're still friends  hahaha)<br><br>We do have a degree of tanking abilities, though nothing like that of a warrior.  You're also no good to a group if you jump in to tank and get yourself killed.  Work on your wisdom items.  If you want dex and agility, just throw yoursefl a buff or two.<br><br>/em waves to Val and blows him a victory kiss  :-p<br>&nbsp;<br>Badjur<br>Oracle of Novus Invictus<br>(Druzzil Ro)<br><br>Aepox Weeblatter<br>51 Dwarf Warrior</td></tr>
