<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=97805880318281></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f97805880318281><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=97805880318281>RE: Switching to Shaman?</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=97805880318281#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=492><span id=Sage>Gorthin</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>149 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Dec 29th 3:01 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[4.95]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, I will take a crack at this =)<br><br>Druids and Shamen are actually quite similar with a few, albeit striking differences.&nbsp;&nbsp;We both overlap in a lot of areas.<br><br>1)Healing.  Both classes are comparable healers.  We get the straight healing spells at the same levels (1, 9, 19, 29, 53).  Shamen get the regen line a little quicker and get upgrades to it quicker (regeneration and chloroplast).  However, druids get the pack versions of these (they affect the whole party).  I would actually call the healing ability a tie, simply because most Shamen are alteration based specialists at higher level and can squeeze out a few more heals than a similary equipped Druid, who tends to be evocation based.  But the pack regen spells are QUITE nice.<br><br>2)Direct Damage.  Druids win here simply because they get a larger variety of Direct Damage, and theirs is MUCH more mana efficient.  But Shamen can do this also, especially early on (level 14 and a 75 point DD).<br><br>3)DoTs (Damage over time).  Both classes enjoy a set of really nice DoTs.  Druids win early on (Stinging swarm and creeping crud), shamen win mid levels (Venom of the Snake, Envenomed Bolt), then Druids sneak back ahead at high levels.  The two advantages we have over Druids here are: a)ALL, yes ALL of our poison based DoTs stack b)Poison DoTs do their damage a tad quicker.  Basically a tossup.<br><br>4)Debuffing.  We win.  Period.  Druids get Snare and Ensnare (&gt;Great&lt; spells), and Flame lick and Immolate type spells, we get Cripple and the Slow line.  No contest =)  I will mention roots here also.  Druids roots kick so much butt since they have been fixed.  My Druid loves her Root line =)  Shamen roots are just a rehash of Wizard ones, so Druids win the root war.<br><br>5)Buffing.  Druids get better AC and HP buffs.  We get better Stat buffs.  We also get a quickness line of spells.  A shaman can buff circles around a Druid, but their damage shields are quite nice, also.  We win, but not as clearly as in the debuffing.<br><br>6)Melee.  HAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHHAHAHAHAHA!  Oh, sorry about that *whew, lemme catch my breath*.  Compared to a tank, we are worthless at higher levels, but we can chip in.  Shamen tend to have better physical stats, so we edge out Druids here.  But after level 40, the times you actually melee are so few and far inbetween, you will forget what your autoattack key is =)<br><br>7) SoW.  Druids at 14, Shamen at 9.  Plus everyone acts like Druids are the only ones who have SoW, so we are spared the constant begging.  We win here =)<br><br>Major Differences.<br>Them: Teleports.  Teleports.  Teleports.  Did I mention Teleports?  Wolf Form.  Teleports.  Evacs.  Um, Teleports?  <br><br>Us:  Useful Pet.  Alchemy.  Cool epic quest mini items =)<br>In general easier for a Shaman to get solid AC and Wis without mega twinking than a Druid.  With our slow line, we can actually tank high level stuff.  Watch that druid get chewed into wolf kibble =)<br><br>I am sure someone can point out more, but those seem to be the major ones to me.<br><br>Gorthin Spiritcaller<br>51 Shaman Bristlebane<br>35 Druid Bristlebane<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
